author: @wahco80
text: üéØ Key Takeaways for quick navigation:  Logistic regression predicts whether something is true or false, not continuous values like linear regression. It uses an S-shaped logistic function to determine the probability of an event (e.g., mouse obesity) based on input variables (e.g., weight). Logistic regression is commonly used for classification tasks where a probability threshold (e.g., 50%) is used to classify samples. It can work with both continuous data (e.g., weight and age) and discrete data (e.g., genotype and astrological sign). Unlike linear regression, logistic regression uses maximum likelihood instead of least squares to fit the line to the data. Variables' significance in logistic regression is determined by testing if their effect on the prediction is significantly different from zero using Wald's tests.  Made with HARPA AI

author: @abpokeunite3463
text: 00:00 Logistic regression is a technique for traditional statistics and machine learning.  01:05 Linear and multiple regression are forms of machine learning used to predict size based on weight and blood volume.  02:13 Linear regression can predict size using genotype and multiple variables  03:09 Logistic regression predicts true/false instead of continuous values  04:22 Logistic regression can predict obesity based on weight, genotype, age, and astrological sign.  05:34 Logistic regression is a popular machine learning method.  06:36 Linear regression uses residuals to minimize sum of squares and calculate r squared  07:45 Logistic regression can classify samples and assess useful variables.

author: @billb3324
text: Thanks for these awesome videos Josh! I'm watching through many of them today. This one is really good, though I think you made a mistake when you chose "obesity" as your categorical variable. It's confusing because it is not really a categorical variable, it's a somewhat arbitrary split of the continuous data (weight). Then you are using weight as a predictor variable in your model, which adds to the confusion. Maybe a traditional "having X disease or not" would be a better categorical variable.   I also think that you should connect the dots more for students in terms of why we are running this model - the inferential part of inferential statistics. We don't really care that much about these particular mice, they are the ones that help us create the model. The model is for understanding a new mouse that was not in the model - we may not be able to directly measure if it has the disease or not, but we can make an educated guess about that by taking some measurements of things that we can easily observe, the predictors in your model.   Again these are very well done videos, love them!

author: @jeffnador9594
text: Worth saying that you can compare models in logistic regression, just not with the same approach as linear regression. One simple way, for instance is using the Akaike Information Criterion (or AIC); it's calculated by taking the natural log of the likelihood function, and subtracting it from the number of predictors in the model, then doubling that difference: 2[k - ln(likelihood function)]. Once you've calculated it for each model, the one with the *lowest* AIC is the most parsimonious. That is, it does the best job of fitting the data with the fewest predictors.  You can do something similar to get Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC), and if you take the quotient of two BICs, you've got a Bayes factor that you can use to compare the evidence for or against either model.
